## Description {#details}

Implements a lazy call graph analysis and related passes for the new pass manager.

NB: This is <em>not</em> a traditional call graph! It is a graph which models both the current calls and potential calls. As a consequence there are many edges in this call graph that do not correspond to a &#39;call&#39; or &#39;invoke&#39; instruction.

The primary use cases of this graph analysis is to facilitate iterating across the functions of a module in ways that ensure all callees are visited prior to a caller (given any SCC constraints), or vice versa. As such is it particularly well suited to organizing CGSCC optimizations such as inlining, outlining, argument promotion, etc. That is its primary use case and motivates the design. It may not be appropriate for other purposes. The use graph of functions or some other conservative analysis of call instructions may be interesting for optimizations and subsequent analyses which don&#39;t work in the context of an overly specified potential-call-edge graph.

To understand the specific rules and nature of this call graph analysis, see the documentation of the <code>LazyCallGraph</code> below.

<Link id="l00062" /><CodeLine lineNumber="62"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// A lazily constructed view of the call graph of a module.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00063" /><CodeLine lineNumber="63"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00064" /><CodeLine lineNumber="64"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// With the edges of this graph, the motivating constraint that we are</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00065" /><CodeLine lineNumber="65"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// attempting to maintain is that function-local optimization, CGSCC-local</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00066" /><CodeLine lineNumber="66"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// optimizations, and optimizations transforming a pair of functions connected</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00067" /><CodeLine lineNumber="67"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// by an edge in the graph, do not invalidate a bottom-up traversal of the SCC</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00068" /><CodeLine lineNumber="68"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// DAG. That is, no optimizations will delete, remove, or add an edge such</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00069" /><CodeLine lineNumber="69"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// that functions already visited in a bottom-up order of the SCC DAG are no</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00070" /><CodeLine lineNumber="70"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// longer valid to have visited, or such that functions not yet visited in</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00071" /><CodeLine lineNumber="71"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// a bottom-up order of the SCC DAG are not required to have already been</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00072" /><CodeLine lineNumber="72"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// visited.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00073" /><CodeLine lineNumber="73"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00074" /><CodeLine lineNumber="74"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Within this constraint, the desire is to minimize the merge points of the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00075" /><CodeLine lineNumber="75"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// SCC DAG. The greater the fanout of the SCC DAG and the fewer merge points</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00076" /><CodeLine lineNumber="76"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// in the SCC DAG, the more independence there is in optimizing within it.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00077" /><CodeLine lineNumber="77"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// There is a strong desire to enable parallelization of optimizations over</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00078" /><CodeLine lineNumber="78"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// the call graph, and both limited fanout and merge points will (artificially</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00079" /><CodeLine lineNumber="79"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// in some cases) limit the scaling of such an effort.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00080" /><CodeLine lineNumber="80"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00081" /><CodeLine lineNumber="81"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// To this end, graph represents both direct and any potential resolution to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00082" /><CodeLine lineNumber="82"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// an indirect call edge. Another way to think about it is that it represents</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00083" /><CodeLine lineNumber="83"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// both the direct call edges and any direct call edges that might be formed</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00084" /><CodeLine lineNumber="84"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// through static optimizations. Specifically, it considers taking the address</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00085" /><CodeLine lineNumber="85"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// of a function to be an edge in the call graph because this might be</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00086" /><CodeLine lineNumber="86"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// forwarded to become a direct call by some subsequent function-local</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00087" /><CodeLine lineNumber="87"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// optimization. The result is that the graph closely follows the use-def</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00088" /><CodeLine lineNumber="88"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// edges for functions. Walking &quot;up&quot; the graph can be done by looking at all</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00089" /><CodeLine lineNumber="89"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// of the uses of a function.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00090" /><CodeLine lineNumber="90"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00091" /><CodeLine lineNumber="91"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// The roots of the call graph are the external functions and functions</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00092" /><CodeLine lineNumber="92"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// escaped into global variables. Those functions can be called from outside</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00093" /><CodeLine lineNumber="93"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// of the module or via unknowable means in the IR -- we may not be able to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00094" /><CodeLine lineNumber="94"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// form even a potential call edge from a function body which may dynamically</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00095" /><CodeLine lineNumber="95"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// load the function and call it.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00096" /><CodeLine lineNumber="96"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00097" /><CodeLine lineNumber="97"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// This analysis still requires updates to remain valid after optimizations</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00098" /><CodeLine lineNumber="98"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// which could potentially change the set of potential callees. The</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00099" /><CodeLine lineNumber="99"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// constraints it operates under only make the traversal order remain valid.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00100" /><CodeLine lineNumber="100"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00101" /><CodeLine lineNumber="101"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// The entire analysis must be re-computed if full interprocedural</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00102" /><CodeLine lineNumber="102"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// optimizations run at any point. For example, globalopt completely</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00103" /><CodeLine lineNumber="103"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// invalidates the information in this analysis.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00104" /><CodeLine lineNumber="104"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00105" /><CodeLine lineNumber="105"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// FIXME: This class is named LazyCallGraph in a lame attempt to distinguish</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00106" /><CodeLine lineNumber="106"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// it from the existing CallGraph. At some point, it is expected that this</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00107" /><CodeLine lineNumber="107"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// will be the only call graph and it will be renamed accordingly.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00108" /><CodeLine lineNumber="108" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">class </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/#a58d534b072f7d0fa5f54ff569bb745ec">LazyCallGraph</a> &#123;</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00114" /><CodeLine lineNumber="114"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// A class used to represent edges in the call graph.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00115" /><CodeLine lineNumber="115"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00116" /><CodeLine lineNumber="116"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// The lazy call graph models both &#42;call&#42; edges and &#42;reference&#42; edges. Call</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00117" /><CodeLine lineNumber="117"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// edges are much what you would expect, and exist when there is a &#39;call&#39; or</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00118" /><CodeLine lineNumber="118"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// &#39;invoke&#39; instruction of some function. Reference edges are also tracked</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00119" /><CodeLine lineNumber="119"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// along side these, and exist whenever any instruction (transitively</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00120" /><CodeLine lineNumber="120"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// through its operands) references a function. All call edges are</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00121" /><CodeLine lineNumber="121"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// inherently reference edges, and so the reference graph forms a superset</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00122" /><CodeLine lineNumber="122"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// of the formal call graph.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00123" /><CodeLine lineNumber="123"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00124" /><CodeLine lineNumber="124"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// All of these forms of edges are fundamentally represented as outgoing</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00125" /><CodeLine lineNumber="125"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// edges. The edges are stored in the source node and point at the target</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00126" /><CodeLine lineNumber="126"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// node. This allows the edge structure itself to be a very compact data</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00127" /><CodeLine lineNumber="127"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// structure: essentially a tagged pointer.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00128" /><CodeLine lineNumber="128" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/edge"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">class </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/edge/#a97e3e2913f67539740641df7f922826d">Edge</a> &#123;</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00302" /><CodeLine lineNumber="302"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// A node in the call graph.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00303" /><CodeLine lineNumber="303"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00304" /><CodeLine lineNumber="304"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// This represents a single node. Its primary roles are to cache the list of</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00305" /><CodeLine lineNumber="305"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// callees, de-duplicate and provide fast testing of whether a function is a</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00306" /><CodeLine lineNumber="306"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// callee, and facilitate iteration of child nodes in the graph.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00307" /><CodeLine lineNumber="307"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00308" /><CodeLine lineNumber="308"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// The node works much like an optional in order to lazily populate the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00309" /><CodeLine lineNumber="309"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// edges of each node. Until populated, there are no edges. Once populated,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00310" /><CodeLine lineNumber="310"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// you can access the edges by dereferencing the node or using the &#96;-&gt;&#96;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00311" /><CodeLine lineNumber="311"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// operator as if the node was an &#96;std::optional&lt;EdgeSequence&gt;&#96;.</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00520" /><CodeLine lineNumber="520"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// A RefSCC of the call graph.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00521" /><CodeLine lineNumber="521"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00522" /><CodeLine lineNumber="522"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// This models a Strongly Connected Component of function reference edges in</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00523" /><CodeLine lineNumber="523"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// the call graph. As opposed to actual SCCs, these can be used to scope</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00524" /><CodeLine lineNumber="524"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// subgraphs of the module which are independent from other subgraphs of the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00525" /><CodeLine lineNumber="525"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// module because they do not reference it in any way. This is also the unit</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00526" /><CodeLine lineNumber="526"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// where we do mutation of the graph in order to restrict mutations to those</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00527" /><CodeLine lineNumber="527"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// which don&#39;t violate this independence.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00528" /><CodeLine lineNumber="528"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00529" /><CodeLine lineNumber="529"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// A RefSCC contains a DAG of actual SCCs. All the nodes within the RefSCC</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00530" /><CodeLine lineNumber="530"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// are necessarily within some actual SCC that nests within it. Since</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00531" /><CodeLine lineNumber="531"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// a direct call &#42;is&#42; a reference, there will always be at least one RefSCC</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00532" /><CodeLine lineNumber="532"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// around any SCC.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00533" /><CodeLine lineNumber="533"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00534" /><CodeLine lineNumber="534"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Spurious ref edges, meaning ref edges that still exist in the call graph</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00535" /><CodeLine lineNumber="535"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// even though the corresponding IR reference no longer exists, are allowed.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00536" /><CodeLine lineNumber="536"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// This is mostly to support argument promotion, which can modify a caller to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00537" /><CodeLine lineNumber="537"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// no longer pass a function. The only place that needs to specially handle</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00538" /><CodeLine lineNumber="538"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// this is deleting a dead function/node, otherwise the dead ref edges are</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00539" /><CodeLine lineNumber="539"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// automatically removed when visiting the function/node no longer containing</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00540" /><CodeLine lineNumber="540"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// the ref edge.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00541" /><CodeLine lineNumber="541" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/refscc"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">class </span><span class="doxyHighlight">RefSCC &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00542" /><CodeLine lineNumber="542" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/refscc/#a81774ea46253e6427d63a610bd624c08"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">friend</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">class </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/refscc/#a81774ea46253e6427d63a610bd624c08">LazyCallGraph</a>;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00543" /><CodeLine lineNumber="543" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/refscc/#a3a7a57d977301c68294ee8d4c92543ce"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">friend</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">class </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/node">LazyCallGraph::Node</a>;</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00545" /><CodeLine lineNumber="545"><span class="doxyHighlight">    <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/refscc/#a81774ea46253e6427d63a610bd624c08">LazyCallGraph</a> &#42;G;</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00663" /><CodeLine lineNumber="663"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// These methods provide the core API for updating the call graph in the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00664" /><CodeLine lineNumber="664"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// presence of (potentially still in-flight) DFS-found RefSCCs and SCCs.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00665" /><CodeLine lineNumber="665"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00666" /><CodeLine lineNumber="666"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// Note that these methods sometimes have complex runtimes, so be careful</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00667" /><CodeLine lineNumber="667"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// how you call them.</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00669" /><CodeLine lineNumber="669"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// Make an existing internal ref edge into a call edge.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00670" /><CodeLine lineNumber="670"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00671" /><CodeLine lineNumber="671"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// This may form a larger cycle and thus collapse SCCs into TargetN&#39;s SCC.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00672" /><CodeLine lineNumber="672"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// If that happens, the optional callback \\p MergedCB will be invoked (if</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00673" /><CodeLine lineNumber="673"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// provided) on the SCCs being merged away prior to actually performing</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00674" /><CodeLine lineNumber="674"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// the merge. Note that this will never include the target SCC as that</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00675" /><CodeLine lineNumber="675"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// will be the SCC functions are merged into to resolve the cycle. Once</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00676" /><CodeLine lineNumber="676"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// this function returns, these merged SCCs are not in a valid state but</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00677" /><CodeLine lineNumber="677"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// the pointers will remain valid until destruction of the parent graph</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00678" /><CodeLine lineNumber="678"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// instance for the purpose of clearing cached information. This function</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00679" /><CodeLine lineNumber="679"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// also returns &#39;true&#39; if a cycle was formed and some SCCs merged away as</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00680" /><CodeLine lineNumber="680"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// a convenience.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00681" /><CodeLine lineNumber="681"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00682" /><CodeLine lineNumber="682"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// After this operation, both SourceN&#39;s SCC and TargetN&#39;s SCC may move</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00683" /><CodeLine lineNumber="683"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// position within this RefSCC&#39;s postorder list. Any SCCs merged are</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00684" /><CodeLine lineNumber="684"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// merged into the TargetN&#39;s SCC in order to preserve reachability analyses</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00685" /><CodeLine lineNumber="685"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// which took place on that SCC.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00686" /><CodeLine lineNumber="686"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">bool</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/refscc/#a2957918db7f91f405b11d92c1ebf3b0f">switchInternalEdgeToCall</a>(</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00687" /><CodeLine lineNumber="687"><span class="doxyHighlight">        <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/node">Node</a> &amp;SourceN, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/node">Node</a> &amp;TargetN,</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00691" /><CodeLine lineNumber="691"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// edge.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00692" /><CodeLine lineNumber="692"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00698" /><CodeLine lineNumber="698"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// Make an existing internal call edge within a single SCC into a ref</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00699" /><CodeLine lineNumber="699"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// edge.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00700" /><CodeLine lineNumber="700"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00701" /><CodeLine lineNumber="701"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// Since SourceN and TargetN are part of a single SCC, this SCC may be</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00702" /><CodeLine lineNumber="702"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// split up due to breaking a cycle in the call edges that formed it. If</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00703" /><CodeLine lineNumber="703"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// that happens, then this routine will insert new SCCs into the postorder</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00704" /><CodeLine lineNumber="704"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// list &#42;before&#42; the SCC of TargetN (previously the SCC of both). This</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00706" /><CodeLine lineNumber="706"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// definition of previously being in a single SCC formed by the cycle from</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00708" /><CodeLine lineNumber="708"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00709" /><CodeLine lineNumber="709"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// The newly added SCCs are added &#42;immediately&#42; and contiguously</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00711" /><CodeLine lineNumber="711"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// the RefSCC&#39;s postorder sequence. You can directly iterate the returned</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00712" /><CodeLine lineNumber="712"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// range to observe all of the new SCCs in postorder.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00713" /><CodeLine lineNumber="713"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00714" /><CodeLine lineNumber="714"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// Note that if SourceN and TargetN are in separate SCCs, the simpler</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00715" /><CodeLine lineNumber="715"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// routine &#96;switchTrivialInternalEdgeToRef&#96; should be used instead.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00716" /><CodeLine lineNumber="716"><span class="doxyHighlight">    <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/iterator-range">iterator&#95;range&lt;iterator&gt;</a> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/refscc/#a96fe0cb15ded58bd1824fa4e3daec680">switchInternalEdgeToRef</a>(<a href="/docs/api/classes/node">Node</a> &amp;SourceN,</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00731" /><CodeLine lineNumber="731"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// Insert a ref edge from one node in this RefSCC to another in this</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00733" /><CodeLine lineNumber="733"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00734" /><CodeLine lineNumber="734"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// This is always a trivial operation as it doesn&#39;t change any part of the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00735" /><CodeLine lineNumber="735"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// graph structure besides connecting the two nodes.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00736" /><CodeLine lineNumber="736"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00737" /><CodeLine lineNumber="737"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// Note that we don&#39;t support directly inserting internal &#42;call&#42; edges</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00751" /><CodeLine lineNumber="751"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">void</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/refscc/#a743c2ac21f2f8a8c6af18e1e09f13229">insertOutgoingEdge</a>(<a href="/docs/api/classes/node">Node</a> &amp;SourceN, <a href="/docs/api/classes/node">Node</a> &amp;TargetN, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/edge/#a8a5508e6c049172373b05c47c1b6fe13">Edge::Kind</a> EK);</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00752" /><CodeLine lineNumber="752"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00753" /><CodeLine lineNumber="753"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// Insert an edge whose source is in a descendant RefSCC and target is in</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00754" /><CodeLine lineNumber="754"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// this RefSCC.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00755" /><CodeLine lineNumber="755"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00756" /><CodeLine lineNumber="756"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// There must be an existing path from the target to the source in this</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00757" /><CodeLine lineNumber="757"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// case.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00758" /><CodeLine lineNumber="758"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00759" /><CodeLine lineNumber="759"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// NB! This is has the potential to be a very expensive function. It</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00760" /><CodeLine lineNumber="760"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// inherently forms a cycle in the prior RefSCC DAG and we have to merge</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00761" /><CodeLine lineNumber="761"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// RefSCCs to resolve that cycle. But finding all of the RefSCCs which</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00762" /><CodeLine lineNumber="762"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// participate in the cycle can in the worst case require traversing every</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00763" /><CodeLine lineNumber="763"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// RefSCC in the graph. Every attempt is made to avoid that, but passes</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00764" /><CodeLine lineNumber="764"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// must still exercise caution calling this routine repeatedly.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00765" /><CodeLine lineNumber="765"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00766" /><CodeLine lineNumber="766"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// Also note that this can only insert ref edges. In order to insert</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00767" /><CodeLine lineNumber="767"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// a call edge, first insert a ref edge and then switch it to a call edge.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00768" /><CodeLine lineNumber="768"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// These are intentionally kept as separate interfaces because each step</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00769" /><CodeLine lineNumber="769"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// of the operation invalidates a different set of data structures.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00770" /><CodeLine lineNumber="770"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00771" /><CodeLine lineNumber="771"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// This returns all the RefSCCs which were merged into the this RefSCC</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00772" /><CodeLine lineNumber="772"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// (the target&#39;s). This allows callers to invalidate any cached</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00773" /><CodeLine lineNumber="773"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// information.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00774" /><CodeLine lineNumber="774"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00775" /><CodeLine lineNumber="775"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// FIXME: We could possibly optimize this quite a bit for cases where the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00776" /><CodeLine lineNumber="776"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// caller and callee are very nearby in the graph. See comments in the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00777" /><CodeLine lineNumber="777"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// implementation for details, but that use case might impact users.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00778" /><CodeLine lineNumber="778"><span class="doxyHighlight">    <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/smallvector">SmallVector&lt;RefSCC &#42;, 1&gt;</a> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/refscc/#a01b1581633bb40f86d6dc62a1c1a7f72">insertIncomingRefEdge</a>(<a href="/docs/api/classes/node">Node</a> &amp;SourceN,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00779" /><CodeLine lineNumber="779"><span class="doxyHighlight">                                                   <a href="/docs/api/classes/node">Node</a> &amp;TargetN);</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00780" /><CodeLine lineNumber="780"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00781" /><CodeLine lineNumber="781"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// Remove an edge whose source is in this RefSCC and target is &#42;not&#42;.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00782" /><CodeLine lineNumber="782"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00783" /><CodeLine lineNumber="783"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// This removes an inter-RefSCC edge. All inter-RefSCC edges originating</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00784" /><CodeLine lineNumber="784"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// from this SCC have been fully explored by any in-flight DFS graph</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00785" /><CodeLine lineNumber="785"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// formation, so this is always safe to call once you have the source</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00786" /><CodeLine lineNumber="786"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// RefSCC.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00787" /><CodeLine lineNumber="787"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00788" /><CodeLine lineNumber="788"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// This operation does not change the cyclic structure of the graph and so</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00789" /><CodeLine lineNumber="789"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// is very inexpensive. It may change the connectivity graph of the SCCs</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00790" /><CodeLine lineNumber="790"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// though, so be careful calling this while iterating over them.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00791" /><CodeLine lineNumber="791"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">void</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/lazycallgraph/refscc/#ab130250bcdaefbfd3c583cad7b120b62">removeOutgoingEdge</a>(<a href="/docs/api/classes/node">Node</a> &amp;SourceN, <a href="/docs/api/classes/node">Node</a> &amp;TargetN);</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00792" /><CodeLine lineNumber="792"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00793" /><CodeLine lineNumber="793"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// Remove a list of ref edges which are entirely within this RefSCC.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00794" /><CodeLine lineNumber="794"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00795" /><CodeLine lineNumber="795"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// Both the \\a SourceN and all of the \\a TargetNs must be within this</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00796" /><CodeLine lineNumber="796"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// RefSCC. Removing these edges may break cycles that form this RefSCC and</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00797" /><CodeLine lineNumber="797"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// thus this operation may change the RefSCC graph significantly. In</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00798" /><CodeLine lineNumber="798"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// particular, this operation will re-form new RefSCCs based on the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00799" /><CodeLine lineNumber="799"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// remaining connectivity of the graph. The following invariants are</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00800" /><CodeLine lineNumber="800"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// guaranteed to hold after calling this method:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00801" /><CodeLine lineNumber="801"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00802" /><CodeLine lineNumber="802"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// 1) If a ref-cycle remains after removal, it leaves this RefSCC intact</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00803" /><CodeLine lineNumber="803"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///    and in the graph. No new RefSCCs are built.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00804" /><CodeLine lineNumber="804"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// 2) Otherwise, this RefSCC will be dead after this call and no longer in</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00805" /><CodeLine lineNumber="805"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///    the graph or the postorder traversal of the call graph. Any iterator</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00806" /><CodeLine lineNumber="806"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///    pointing at this RefSCC will become invalid.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00807" /><CodeLine lineNumber="807"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// 3) All newly formed RefSCCs will be returned and the order of the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00808" /><CodeLine lineNumber="808"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///    RefSCCs returned will be a valid postorder traversal of the new</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00809" /><CodeLine lineNumber="809"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///    RefSCCs.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00810" /><CodeLine lineNumber="810"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// 4) No RefSCC other than this RefSCC has its member set changed (this is</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00811" /><CodeLine lineNumber="811"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///    inherent in the definition of removing such an edge).</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00812" /><CodeLine lineNumber="812"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00813" /><CodeLine lineNumber="813"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// These invariants are very important to ensure that we can build</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00814" /><CodeLine lineNumber="814"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// optimization pipelines on top of the CGSCC pass manager which</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00815" /><CodeLine lineNumber="815"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// intelligently update the RefSCC graph without invalidating other parts</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00816" /><CodeLine lineNumber="816"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// of the RefSCC graph.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00817" /><CodeLine lineNumber="817"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00818" /><CodeLine lineNumber="818"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// Note that we provide no routine to remove a &#42;call&#42; edge. Instead, you</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00819" /><CodeLine lineNumber="819"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// must first switch it to a ref edge using \\c switchInternalEdgeToRef.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00820" /><CodeLine lineNumber="820"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// This split API is intentional as each of these two steps can invalidate</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00821" /><CodeLine lineNumber="821"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// a different aspect of the graph structure and needs to have the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00822" /><CodeLine lineNumber="822"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// invalidation handled independently.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00823" /><CodeLine lineNumber="823"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00824" /><CodeLine lineNumber="824"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// The runtime complexity of this method is, in the worst case, O(V+E)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00825" /><CodeLine lineNumber="825"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// where V is the number of nodes in this RefSCC and E is the number of</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00826" /><CodeLine lineNumber="826"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// edges leaving the nodes in this RefSCC. Note that E includes both edges</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00827" /><CodeLine lineNumber="827"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// within this RefSCC and edges from this RefSCC to child RefSCCs. Some</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00828" /><CodeLine lineNumber="828"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// effort has been made to minimize the overhead of common cases such as</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00829" /><CodeLine lineNumber="829"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// self-edges and edge removals which result in a spanning tree with no</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00830" /><CodeLine lineNumber="830"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// more cycles.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00831" /><CodeLine lineNumber="831"><span class="doxyHighlight">    &#91;&#91;nodiscard&#93;&#93; <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/smallvector">SmallVector&lt;RefSCC &#42;, 1&gt;</a></span></CodeLine>
